WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.295 --> 00:00:03.035
As a designer, you live and breathe the visual, right?

2
00:00:03.295 --> 00:00:06.235
You craft every single pixel, every color, every bit

3
00:00:06.235 --> 00:00:08.715
of layout to create this perfect experience.

4
00:00:09.215 --> 00:00:10.315
But what if I told you

5
00:00:10.505 --> 00:00:13.075
that every design you make has a secret identity,

6
00:00:13.595 --> 00:00:16.115
a second life that millions of people experience not

7
00:00:16.115 --> 00:00:17.995
with their eyes, but with their ears.

8
00:00:18.585 --> 00:00:21.995
It's time we uncovered what your designs really sound like.

9
00:00:23.025 --> 00:00:24.765
So that's the big question for today.

10
00:00:25.075 --> 00:00:27.165
What does your design sound like?

11
00:00:27.705 --> 00:00:28.765
And once you get the answer,

12
00:00:28.865 --> 00:00:30.765
you're gonna gain this new kind of superpower.

13
00:00:31.105 --> 00:00:33.805
The ability to actually hear your own designs

14
00:00:33.825 --> 00:00:36.005
and make sure they work for absolutely everyone.

15
00:00:37.055 --> 00:00:39.145
Okay, so here's the big reveal.

16
00:00:39.415 --> 00:00:41.665
Running parallel to your beautiful pixel,

17
00:00:41.665 --> 00:00:42.865
perfect visual design.

18
00:00:43.055 --> 00:00:44.705
There's a whole other interface.

19
00:00:45.055 --> 00:00:46.945
It's a hidden one, a structural one.

20
00:00:47.205 --> 00:00:49.545
You can't see it, but it is absolutely essential

21
00:00:49.545 --> 00:00:51.545
for anyone using assistive technology.

22
00:00:52.295 --> 00:00:54.435
That's right. Things like screen readers,

23
00:00:54.745 --> 00:00:57.235
they don't process your visual styling,

24
00:00:57.425 --> 00:00:58.955
they don't care about your brand colors

25
00:00:59.015 --> 00:01:01.315
or that elegant white space you spent hours on.

26
00:01:01.745 --> 00:01:03.075
Nope. They interact

27
00:01:03.075 --> 00:01:05.115
with a totally different layer of information.

28
00:01:05.615 --> 00:01:07.755
One that's all about structure and meaning.

29
00:01:08.605 --> 00:01:10.505
Now, I know this might sound a little technical,

30
00:01:10.525 --> 00:01:11.945
but I promise you it's not.

31
00:01:12.525 --> 00:01:16.065
The way your designs meaning gets translated into sound is

32
00:01:16.385 --> 00:01:17.865
actually a pretty straightforward process.

33
00:01:18.555 --> 00:01:20.745
Let's just quickly walk through how it all happens.

34
00:01:21.725 --> 00:01:23.625
It all starts with you, right?

35
00:01:23.625 --> 00:01:25.745
Inside your design file, your choices,

36
00:01:26.125 --> 00:01:28.505
the components you use, the little notes you leave

37
00:01:28.505 --> 00:01:30.225
for engineers, that's the blueprint.

38
00:01:30.495 --> 00:01:32.585
From there, engineering brings it all to life.

39
00:01:33.165 --> 00:01:35.465
And as they do a sort of simplified map

40
00:01:35.465 --> 00:01:37.225
of your design gets created automatically,

41
00:01:37.645 --> 00:01:39.905
and that map is what gets turned into sound.

42
00:01:40.685 --> 00:01:42.905
And that simplified map, it has a name,

43
00:01:43.125 --> 00:01:44.345
the accessibility tree.

44
00:01:44.845 --> 00:01:46.265
The best way to think of it is like this.

45
00:01:46.615 --> 00:01:48.345
Your full design is like a massive,

46
00:01:48.695 --> 00:01:50.345
complex architectural blueprint.

47
00:01:50.765 --> 00:01:52.745
The accessibility tree, on the other hand,

48
00:01:52.765 --> 00:01:55.225
is more like the simple directory in a building's lobby.

49
00:01:55.565 --> 00:01:56.625
It doesn't show you the plumbing

50
00:01:56.685 --> 00:01:58.585
or the wiring, it just tells you where

51
00:01:58.585 --> 00:01:59.905
to find the important stuff, you know,

52
00:01:59.905 --> 00:02:01.145
like the buttons and the headings.

53
00:02:02.055 --> 00:02:04.555
So how does this building directory describe everything?

54
00:02:05.065 --> 00:02:07.195
Well, it uses a really simple language

55
00:02:07.195 --> 00:02:09.315
that's built on just four core properties.

56
00:02:09.745 --> 00:02:10.955
Once you know these four things,

57
00:02:11.095 --> 00:02:12.595
you can basically understand

58
00:02:12.625 --> 00:02:14.915
what any element in your design is gonna sound like.

59
00:02:15.605 --> 00:02:19.195
These are the magic four name, role, state, and value.

60
00:02:19.575 --> 00:02:21.315
So the role is just its type,

61
00:02:21.415 --> 00:02:23.235
is it a button, a heading, a link.

62
00:02:23.455 --> 00:02:24.635
You actually define this just

63
00:02:24.635 --> 00:02:25.715
by choosing the right component.

64
00:02:26.095 --> 00:02:28.675
The name is simply what it's called, like submit

65
00:02:28.735 --> 00:02:29.955
or profile settings.

66
00:02:30.175 --> 00:02:31.875
You specify that in your annotations.

67
00:02:32.495 --> 00:02:35.155
The state tells us its current condition. Is it disabled?

68
00:02:35.335 --> 00:02:36.595
Is it checked, expanded?

69
00:02:36.895 --> 00:02:38.555
And again, your annotations define this.

70
00:02:38.815 --> 00:02:40.635
And finally, value, which is really

71
00:02:40.635 --> 00:02:41.835
for things like sliders or

72
00:02:41.835 --> 00:02:42.835
Text fields.

73
00:02:43.195 --> 00:02:45.015
So here's how that all comes together.

74
00:02:45.535 --> 00:02:47.535
A screen reader, user doesn't just hear submit.

75
00:02:47.805 --> 00:02:50.375
They hear the full picture submit form.

76
00:02:50.475 --> 00:02:51.975
That's the name button.

77
00:02:52.155 --> 00:02:55.175
That's the role disabled, and that's its current state.

78
00:02:55.835 --> 00:02:57.895
See, it's clear, it's unambiguous,

79
00:02:57.995 --> 00:02:59.725
and it's super useful, all

80
00:02:59.725 --> 00:03:02.005
because those three properties were defined correctly.

81
00:03:02.705 --> 00:03:05.275
Okay, so now you know the language of this hidden interface.

82
00:03:05.535 --> 00:03:07.075
You can start using your new power.

83
00:03:07.615 --> 00:03:10.875
You can literally look at a visual design and spot problems

84
00:03:10.875 --> 00:03:13.075
before anyone even writes a single line of code.

85
00:03:13.565 --> 00:03:15.195
Let's start with a really important concept.

86
00:03:15.855 --> 00:03:17.835
You gotta know that there are two main ways

87
00:03:17.855 --> 00:03:19.395
to navigate a screen non visually.

88
00:03:19.695 --> 00:03:21.035
The first is the reading order.

89
00:03:21.345 --> 00:03:23.715
This is like reading a book, you know, top to bottom.

90
00:03:24.195 --> 00:03:26.835
A screen reader announces everything in sequence, headings,

91
00:03:26.905 --> 00:03:28.635
buttons, paragraphs, the works,

92
00:03:29.055 --> 00:03:30.595
but the focus order is different.

93
00:03:30.855 --> 00:03:33.835
That's for keyboard users who use the tab key to jump only

94
00:03:33.835 --> 00:03:35.595
between the interactive things like

95
00:03:35.595 --> 00:03:36.795
buttons and input fields.

96
00:03:37.095 --> 00:03:38.915
You've gotta consider both of these paths

97
00:03:38.915 --> 00:03:40.355
to make sure the experience is logical.

98
00:03:40.975 --> 00:03:42.115
And once you have this knowledge,

99
00:03:42.295 --> 00:03:44.995
all these common issues just start to jump out at you.

100
00:03:45.215 --> 00:03:47.275
You'll see three learn more buttons

101
00:03:47.295 --> 00:03:49.275
and immediately realize they'll all sound identical.

102
00:03:49.535 --> 00:03:51.675
You'll spot that beautiful little trash can icon

103
00:03:51.675 --> 00:03:52.995
and think, wait, what's its name?

104
00:03:53.495 --> 00:03:55.355
You'll see an accordion that looks open

105
00:03:55.535 --> 00:03:57.235
and question if its expanded state

106
00:03:57.335 --> 00:03:58.555
is actually being announced.

107
00:03:58.895 --> 00:04:00.515
You see, you're already starting

108
00:04:00.515 --> 00:04:02.075
to think like a human screen reader.

109
00:04:02.805 --> 00:04:04.595
Let's just look at this classic example.

110
00:04:05.635 --> 00:04:07.435
Visually, you see three open buttons

111
00:04:07.735 --> 00:04:08.795
and they're next to different items.

112
00:04:08.855 --> 00:04:10.475
So the context is totally clear to you.

113
00:04:11.055 --> 00:04:13.835
But a screen reader user who's just tabbing between buttons,

114
00:04:14.185 --> 00:04:17.235
they just hear open button, then open button

115
00:04:17.535 --> 00:04:21.435
and open button, open what they have no clue.

116
00:04:22.145 --> 00:04:24.315
This is a problem you can now easily spot

117
00:04:24.455 --> 00:04:26.195
and fix with better annotations.

118
00:04:27.015 --> 00:04:29.515
And this brings us to a really important shift in

119
00:04:29.515 --> 00:04:30.675
how you think about your job.

120
00:04:31.375 --> 00:04:33.395
You are not just a visual designer anymore.

121
00:04:33.855 --> 00:04:36.275
You are the architect of the oral experience,

122
00:04:36.615 --> 00:04:37.835
the sound of your interface.

123
00:04:38.095 --> 00:04:40.875
That's your responsibility now, and it's a really creative

124
00:04:40.935 --> 00:04:41.995
and empowering one.

125
00:04:42.725 --> 00:04:43.945
So here's the crucial point.

126
00:04:44.295 --> 00:04:46.505
What you specify is what users will hear.

127
00:04:47.185 --> 00:04:49.425
Engineering teams are amazing, but they're not mind readers.

128
00:04:49.725 --> 00:04:51.825
If the accessible name or the heading level

129
00:04:52.085 --> 00:04:54.225
or a state change isn't in your design spec,

130
00:04:54.325 --> 00:04:55.705
it just won't be in the final product.

131
00:04:56.055 --> 00:04:58.345
Your annotations are the direct source of truth for

132
00:04:58.345 --> 00:04:59.385
that oral experience.

133
00:05:00.495 --> 00:05:02.235
So what should be in your handoff?

134
00:05:02.415 --> 00:05:04.235
Here's a quick little checklist to get you started.

135
00:05:04.685 --> 00:05:07.475
First, make sure every interactive element has a

136
00:05:07.475 --> 00:05:08.715
clear accessible name.

137
00:05:09.375 --> 00:05:10.435
Define your heading levels

138
00:05:10.495 --> 00:05:12.435
to create a logical outline for the page.

139
00:05:13.195 --> 00:05:15.475
Document all the state changes like when an accordion

140
00:05:15.475 --> 00:05:17.115
expands or a checkbox gets checked.

141
00:05:17.495 --> 00:05:19.035
And for images, make the call.

142
00:05:19.215 --> 00:05:20.995
Are they just decorative and can be ignored?

143
00:05:21.255 --> 00:05:23.475
Or are they informative and need a description?

144
00:05:24.145 --> 00:05:25.885
And you wanna hear the best part? You don't have

145
00:05:25.885 --> 00:05:26.965
to just cross your fingers

146
00:05:27.105 --> 00:05:30.085
and trust that your annotations were implemented correctly.

147
00:05:30.425 --> 00:05:32.125
You can actually peek under the hood

148
00:05:32.225 --> 00:05:35.525
and check the accessibility tree yourself right in your web

149
00:05:35.525 --> 00:05:36.765
browser without writing

150
00:05:36.785 --> 00:05:38.605
or even reading a single line of code.

151
00:05:39.585 --> 00:05:42.525
It is surprisingly simple In any major browser,

152
00:05:42.785 --> 00:05:44.125
you can open the developer tools,

153
00:05:44.305 --> 00:05:46.485
and I know developer tools sounds intimidating,

154
00:05:46.685 --> 00:05:49.365
but stick with me and just find the accessibility tab.

155
00:05:49.715 --> 00:05:52.205
From there, you can click on any element on the page

156
00:05:52.305 --> 00:05:54.965
and see its properties, its name, its role,

157
00:05:55.105 --> 00:05:56.925
and its state. You can literally

158
00:05:57.045 --> 00:05:59.445
Check if what was built matches your design spec.

159
00:05:59.835 --> 00:06:02.045
This is a total game changer for designers.

160
00:06:02.925 --> 00:06:04.505
So let's end where we started.

161
00:06:05.005 --> 00:06:07.905
You now have the power to be the human screen reader.

162
00:06:08.445 --> 00:06:11.385
You can look at any interface yours, someone else's,

163
00:06:11.645 --> 00:06:13.225
and see its secret identity.

164
00:06:13.855 --> 00:06:17.345
From this moment on as you're designing, always ask yourself

165
00:06:17.345 --> 00:06:19.385
that one simple, powerful question.

166
00:06:20.015 --> 00:06:21.105
What will this sound like?

167
00:06:21.535 --> 00:06:24.225
Answering it is going to make you a better, more inclusive,

168
00:06:24.445 --> 00:06:26.825
and honestly, a more powerful designer.
